  "prompt": "What are the differences between constitutional, criminal, civil laws?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between constitutional, criminal, and civil laws:\n\nConstitutional Law:\n- Defines fundamental rights and government structure\n- Establishes separation of powers\n- Sets limits on government authority\n- Protects individual rights and liberties\n- Highest level of legal authority in a country\n- Applies to all citizens and government institutions\n\nCriminal Law:\n- Defines criminal offenses and punishments\n- Prosecuted by the government\n- Focuses on protecting public safety\n- Involves criminal charges against individuals\n- Potential penalties include fines, imprisonment, or probation\n- Requires proof \"beyond reasonable doubt\"\n- Maintains societal order and deters criminal behavior\n\nCivil Law:\n- Resolves disputes between private parties\n- Seeks compensation or specific actions\n- Focuses on resolving conflicts and providing remedies\n- Involves monetary damages or specific performance\n- Burden of proof is \"preponderance of evidence\"\n- Covers areas like contracts, property, family disputes\n- Initiated by individuals or organizations\n- Aims to make injured parties whole\n\nKey distinctions:\n- Purpose: Constitutional (structure), Criminal (punishment), Civil (resolution)\n- Parties involved: Constitutional (government/citizens), Criminal (state/defendant), Civil (private parties)\n- Consequences: Different penalties and outcomes for each type of law",
